The May jobs numbers released in the United States were extremely positive, leading the author of the article to wonder if there are enough synonyms for "good" to adequately describe them. The economy added 223,000 jobs, despite being in an expansion for nine years, and the unemployment rate fell to 3.8 percent, an 18-year low. Average hourly earnings also rose by 0.3 percent, with a 2.7 percent increase over the past year. The broader definition of unemployment, including those who have given up looking for a job, fell to 7.6 percent. Additionally, the jobless rate for African-Americans reached a record low of 5.9 percent. Overall, the article concludes that the United States economy is performing well, steadily adding more jobs and increasing wages.